# No Auto-Add Components

Max owns prefab and scene component setup. **Do not** silently add gameplay components at runtime on objects that exist in the editor.

## Rule

- **Do not** use `Components.GetOrCreate<T>()`, `Components.Create<T>()`, or equivalent to add **prefab-owned** or **scene-owned** gameplay components.
- **Do** use `Components.Get<T>()` and log a clear warning when a required component is missing — tell Max which object and component to add in the editor.
- **Do** describe manual editor steps when introducing a new component (where to add it, which prefab/scene object, what to wire).

Use `ComponentRequire.On<T>( gameObject, context )` or `ComponentRequire.WarnIfMissing<T>( ... )` in `Code/ComponentRequire.cs` for consistent warnings.

## Allowed runtime auto-add (exceptions)

| Case | Why |
|------|-----|
| `RagdollEnemyOutline` (+ `HighlightOutline`) on host-spawned ragdoll GO | No prefab — created during knockdown |
| `HighlightOutline` inside outline scripts on the same GO | Engine helper; parent script owns tuning |
| `Highlight` on Main Camera via `EnemyOutlineCameraSetup` | Post-process helper; Max approved keeping this |
| `BallPassAssistCollisionRelay` on arbitrary hit bodies | Created on whatever body the ball touches |
| Child GOs spawned in code (comic bursts, trajectory markers, OOB markers, VFX children) | Programmatic spawn — not editor prefab components |

## Player / ball / camera checklist lives in `ARCHITECTURE.md` § Component wiring

When adding a new `[Property]` component that must be tuned in the inspector, add one line to that section and `NAMING_CANON.md`.

## Good vs bad

- **Good:** `var relay = ComponentRequire.On<TackleImpactRelay>( victim, "PlayerTackle.Knockdown" );` then null-check before use.
- **Bad:** `victim.Components.GetOrCreate<TackleImpactRelay>()` — hides the component from Max until play.
- **Good:** "Add `TackleImpactRelay` to each player class prefab; drag crunch sounds onto Impact SFX."
- **Bad:** Patching the scene file to inject the component.
